>
  <p>I don’t only want OpenClaw for administration or automation. I also want it for creative momentum.</p>

  <p>
    That means using it in places where the real problem is not lack of information, but friction: starting a draft,
    shaping an idea, comparing options, or turning scattered notes into something coherent.
  </p>

  <h2>Where it helps creatively</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>helping me get unstuck on the first version</li>
    <li>reorganizing rough ideas into a structure</li>
    <li>giving me alternate framings or tones</li>
    <li>helping me turn a vague direction into a sharper concept</li>
    <li>preserving momentum when I would otherwise context-switch away</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What I don’t want</h2>

  <p>
    I don’t want creativity to become flattened into generic AI prose. The goal isn’t to outsource the voice. The goal
    is to use OpenClaw to make it easier for me to keep my own voice moving.
  </p>
</PostLayout>
